**MCP has two distinct potential roles — disambiguate before building:**
- MCP as **ingestion source** — server pulls from Halo / Confluence / Snowflake and feeds rows into the existing ingestion pipeline (plugs in at the ingestion-adapter boundary alongside file parsers). This is the primary MCP role for NAS-AI.
- MCP as **query interface** — exposes NAS-AI retrieval as an MCP server so external tools (Open WebUI, Claude, other agents) can query the knowledge base. Secondary role; build after system is proven.
- These are separate pieces of work; may want both, but build/scope one at a time.

**Metadata query path (4.6) — design agreed 2026-06-16:**
- Vault analytics queries ("how many Moore notes", "which notes are in Moore", "what collections exist") should NOT go through the BM25/RAG pipeline — they need direct Postgres queries against metadata fields (category, source_file, collection_name, created_at).
- Stage 0 LLM adds a `metadata_query: true/false` flag. If true + discovery → route to direct Postgres metadata query. If false → existing BM25/RRF path unchanged.
- Content queries ("show all files by Goldman", "what tags contain price") always `metadata_query: false` — they need to read record content, not just metadata. Recon discovery_list behavior is unaffected.
- Metadata path is generic — works for any collection, any format, any doc type — because it queries standard fields every ingested record has.
- **Needs validation:** confirm "show all files by Goldman" on recon stays on BM25 path and returns correct results after metadata path is added. Define test cases before implementing.
- Validation test suite (pre-implementation): (1) "show all files by Goldman" → must stay content-discovery, return broker file list; (2) "how many Moore notes" → must return exact Postgres count (41); (3) "which notes are in Moore" → must return distinct note list from metadata; (4) "how many tags contain price" on FIX → must stay existing discovery_count path.

**Open WebUI evaluation (4.7) — design discussion 2026-06-16:**
- Open WebUI is a local web app that sits on top of local LLMs — connects to LM Studio via OpenAI-compatible API, no external AI, no cloud. Fully compatible with NAS-AI's "local only" requirement.
- If NAS-AI exposes an MCP server (query-interface role), Open WebUI can connect to it and provide a polished conversational interface without requiring custom Streamlit UI maintenance.
- Potential AVD deployment model: Open WebUI deployed once on data-AVD, all users access via browser — no Python environment needed on individual machines.
- Open WebUI MCP support is relatively new — verify maturity before committing.
- Decision point: evaluate when NAS-AI MCP server is ready. Until then, continue with Streamlit.
- **Standing constraint: NAS-AI is fully local. No external AI or cloud model connections, ever.**

**Deployment / hosting (agreed 2026-06-15, refined 2026-06-16):**
- Target users: multiple people on Azure Virtual Desktop (AVD) sessions, same company tenant.
- Data-AVD and login-AVD are likely DISTINCT — app stays a remote-DB client (same pattern as today: Mac → NAS over Tailscale).
- AVD-hosting dissolves the "compiled installer" concern — provision-once, users open in browser.
- Open topology question: Streamlit/Open WebUI app per login-AVD session or shared on data-AVD? Decide at deployment time.
- NAS remains always-available dev/fallback environment regardless of AVD decisions.

**Data sources (open, 2026-06-15):**
- Current: file ingestion (XML, XLSX, CSV, Markdown) — narrow coverage; broadening format testing is near-term priority.
- Future: Halo + Confluence (API access confirmed, testable when ready) + Snowflake cloud DB (possibly primary external source).
- Ingestion-source boundary must stay clean: new sources plug in as adapters alongside file parsers. Retrieval/role/serializer layers stay source-agnostic.
- Once ingested via MCP source adapters, Halo/Confluence/Snowflake data uses same Postgres schema — metadata query path covers it for free.

